stylometry: @RISK replicates a model with different random numbers and reports summary measures. An example of an @ RISK equation would be simulating profit for different order quantities. Based upon the mean, standard deviation, and min/maximum quantities, the user can then analyze their best business decision. The mean is the average result for the specific quantity. A low standard deviation is important because the lower the std dev, the more the user can rely on the data @RISK provides. The minimum and maximum quantities can be used as guidelines for determining the possible outcomes of the data results, on the high and low ends. They are what @RISK bases the mean upon. When you run a simulation with five inputs in a simtable, @RISK runs the model for each of the five inputs andgives us results on average after running the simulation 1000 times for each (1000 iterations).
